The '''Buledi''', '''Buledai''' or '''Burdi''' ({{Lang-bal|بلیدی}}) are a western [[Baloch people|Baloch tribe]]<ref>{{Cite book| last = Scholz| first = Fred| title = Nomadism & colonialism : a hundred years of Baluchistan, 1872-1972| date = 2002| orig-year = 1974| location = Karachi ; Oxford ; New York|publisher = Oxford University Press| isbn = 978-0-19-579638-4| ref = harv}}</ref> of the [[Pakistan]]i provinces of [[Sindh]] and [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]]. They are among the major tribes that settled in the [[Jacobabad District]] of Sind during [[Charles James Napier|Charles Napier]]'s time.<ref>{{Cite book| title = 1998 District census report of Jacobabad| location = Islamabad| publisher = Population Census Organization, Statistics Division, Government of Pakistan| series = Census publication | volume =  17| date = 1999|p = 22}} Named as ''Burgis'' in this source.</ref> The word Buledi derived from the Buleda valley of [[Makran]]. In [[Sindh|Sindh province]] they are also known as ''Bardi''.<ref name="Garg2018">{{cite book|author=Sanjay Garg|title=Studies in Indo-Muslim History by S.H. Hodivala Volume I: A Critical Commentary on Elliot and Dowson’s History of India as Told by Its Own Historians (Vols. I-IV) & Yule and Burnell’s Hobson-Jobson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4U9tDwAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PR12|accessdate=1 November 2018|date=3 September 2018|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-429-75783-9|page=3}}</ref> The tribe is further divided into 51 subtribes including the [[Mugheri]], [[Umrani]], Mastoi, and Sakherani.<ref name="es">{{cite book |title=Buledi |publisher=Encyclopedia Sindhiana |edition=1st |url=http://www.encyclopediasindhiana.org/article.php?Dflt=%D8%A8%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A |language=Sindhi}}</ref>

